%I A397770 #18 Jul 15 2026 23:08:57
%S A397770 9,5,20,40,117,285,747,1951,5229,13493,35009
%N A397770 Number of n-digit Zuckerman numbers.
%C A397770 a(n) >= n: For each k from 1 to n, construct a k-digit number using only digits 1 and 2 that is divisible by 2^k. This is possible by induction: start with 2, and when extending by one digit on the left, choose 1 or 2 to make the new number divisible by the next power of 2. Now take this k-digit number and put n-k ones in front of it. The resulting n-digit number has digit product equal to a power of 2, say 2^t with t <= k. Since the suffix is divisible by 2^k, and the prefix times 10^k is also divisible by 2^k, the whole number is divisible by 2^k, hence divisible by 2^t.
%C A397770 A proof that a(n) >= 2.04^n is given in links.
%H A397770 Qizheng He and Carlo Sanna, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.14812">Counting numbers that are divisible by the product of their digits</a>, arXiv:2403.14812 [math.NT], 2024.
%e A397770 For n = 2, a(2) = 5, since the 5 2-digit Zuckerman numbers are 11, 12, 15, 24 and 36.
%t A397770 ZuckermanCount[n_] := Module[{count = 0},
%t A397770   dfs[d_, num_, prod_] := If[d == n,
%t A397770     If[Mod[num, prod] == 0, count++],
%t A397770     Do[dfs[d + 1, 10 num + k, prod k], {k, 9}]
%t A397770   ];
%t A397770   dfs[0, 0, 1];
%t A397770   count
%t A397770 ];
%t A397770 Table[ZuckermanCount[n], {n, 5}]
%Y A397770 Cf. A007602.
%K A397770 nonn,base,more,new
%O A397770 1,1
%A A397770 _SiYang Hu_, Jul 09 2026
%E A397770 a(9)-a(11) from _Sean A. Irvine_, Jul 15 2026
